ce:section.ce:para:
Next, we evaluate the adsorption energies of Ti adatom based GQDs. The Ti atom is adsorbed at the hollow site with the adsorption energy(
E ads metal
) of −3.43 eV and − 3.58 eV for H-GQD24 and OH-GQD24 respectively as calculated from Eq. (1). See Fig. 5(a) and (b) for the corresponding optimised structures of Ti adatom anchored on f-GQD24. The adsorption energies for the single hydrogen molecule onto the Ti atom supported on GQD are given in Table 6. The first hydrogen molecule adsorbs on Ti_H-GQD24 with an adsorption energy of nearly −1.45 eV and onto Ti_OH-GQD24 with an adsorption energy of −1.51 eV. Following the adsorption, the H2 molecule dissociates with each atom chemisorbing onto the Ti atom and the inter atomic distance between both the hydrogen atoms increasing from 0.75 Å to 2.91 Å on Ti_H-GQD24 and from 0.75 Å to 2.44 Å on Ti_OH-GQD24. See Fig. 5(a1) and (b1) for a representation of the optimised configurations of first H2 molecules adsorbed on the Ti_f-GQD24. The interatomic bond distances viz., HH bond distance after adsorption on Ti atom and the TiH bond distance are given in the Supplementary Table S.T.4. The TiH bond distances (after chemisorbing) for both the functionalizations are the same and are around 1.74 Å.

From the results it is clear that Ti as an adatom can reversibly store three H2 molecules by Kubas type of interaction on all the GQDs. But the weight % of the hydrogen storage is still less than the 5.5 % w/w limit set by the US Department of Energy [92]. Thus the number of Ti adatoms on both planes of GQDs was sequentially increased till the maximum limit (see Fig. 8
                           ). The maximum limit is defined as the maximum number of Ti atoms that can be adsorbed without agglomerating and without distorting the GQD structure. The maximum limit of Ti atoms that can be adsorbed on the H-GQD24 was found to be 4 atoms with two on each surface of the GQD (hereafter referred to as 4Ti-GQD24). Fig. 8 shows the optimised structure of 4 Ti atoms adsorbed on the GQD surface. From the Figure it can be seen that the Ti atoms are adsorbed over the carbon ring. The average adsorption energy (

                                 E
                                 ads
                                 metal

                           ) for Ti atoms is −4.83 eV. The adsorption energy per Ti atom was calculated using Eq. (1). Thus the Ti atoms were adsorbed without agglomerating as can be seen from Fig. 8. All the 4 Ti atoms are adsorbed at the same distance from the GQD surface with the same average TiC bond. Bader charge analysis was done to calculate the charge on each atom. The charge on all 4 Ti atoms was the same and equal to 0.94 e after adsorption. Thus there is the same charge transfer from all the 4 Ti atoms during adsorption. This explains why there is no distortion in the structure of H-GQD24 after adsorption of Ti atoms.

Since each Ti atom can adsorb a maximum of 4 H2 molecules initially 16 H2 molecules were adsorbed on 4Ti-GQD24. The initial position of the H2 molecules is shown in Fig. 8(a). The Ti atoms are labelled as Ti.1, Ti.2, Ti.3 and Ti.4. As it can be seen from Fig. 8(b) all the H2 molecules are adsorbed. From the figure it is seen that the GQD maintain their planar structure after adsorption of the H2. The average adsorption energy per H2 molecule (

                                 E
                                 ads
                                 avg

                           ) is −0.59 eV. After incorporating the zero point energy corrections, the average adsorption energy per H2 molecule (

                                 E
                                 ads
                                 avg

                           ) is −0.64 eV there by validating its potential quasi molecular adsorption of hydrogen. The bond length H2 molecules increase from 0.75 Å to a value between 0.8 and 0.83 Å (see Table 10
                           ) while their corresponding IR stretching frequencies decrease to 3000–3500 cm−1 from 4400 cm−1 proving that all the H2 molecules are partially activated on adsorption.
